## Show / hide logic

```js
editor.on('selectionUpdate', () => scheduleUpdateMenuForIndex(index));
editor.on('transaction', () => scheduleUpdateMenuForIndex(index));
editor.on('blur', () => { /* hide immediately, unless click was on the menu */ });
```

- `selectionUpdate` fires whenever the user changes what text is selected.
- `transaction` fires on any change to the editor's content/state — this includes
  when a Bubble workflow applies formatting (e.g. toggling Bold), so the menu's
  position/visibility stays correct even after a format is applied.
- Both are routed through a small `SETTLE_DELAY_MS` (50ms) debounce
  (`scheduleUpdateMenuForIndex`) rather than calling the update directly. A
  blurred-then-refocused editor can momentarily restore the *previous* selection
  before the click resolves to its real new position, firing a stale event before the
  corrected one arrives a moment later. Debouncing means only the settled state
  actually paints, avoiding a one-frame flash at the wrong position.

**Visibility is gated on `editor.isFocused`, checked on every call.** ProseMirror does
**not** clear its internal selection just because DOM focus moves elsewhere — the
model still reports a valid, non-empty text selection long after you've clicked away.
So `isFocused` (not just "is there a text selection") is the authoritative check;
without it, a later scroll/resize tick, or an unrelated `transaction` fired for any
reason (Bubble re-render, another workflow), would resurrect a menu you already
dismissed, since the stale selection still looks valid.

**Menu shows only for a real, non-collapsed text selection** (once focused) — checked
via `selection.toJSON().type === 'text' && !selection.empty`. Checking `.empty` alone
is not enough: ProseMirror's `NodeSelection` (e.g. arrow-keying onto a horizontal rule
or a table, which can't hold a text cursor inside them) and `CellSelection` (table
cells) can both be non-empty without any text actually being highlighted, which used
to make the menu pop up on plain keyboard navigation. Checking the selection's `type`
filters these out so the menu only ever appears for genuine text highlights.

**Hiding on blur** is now handled directly via `editor.on('blur', ...)`, which fires
reliably the instant this row's editor truly loses focus — cancelling any pending
debounce (so a stale callback can't fire afterward and flash the menu back) and
hiding immediately. The blur handler is skipped when `mousedownWasInsideMenu` is true
**or** when `inputFocusedForIndex[index]` is true (see next section for both), so
clicking a format button, or focusing the menu's own input field, doesn't hide the
very menu being used.

**Outside-click detection** (separate `mousedown` listener on `document`, capture phase):
if a click lands outside both the menu element and its matching editor wrapper, the
menu is hidden directly as a fast-path (blur will also catch it a moment later). This
same listener also sets `mousedownWasInsideMenu` and calls `e.preventDefault()` when
the click landed inside the menu — see next section for why.

