## Letting real form fields (e.g. "Insert Link" URL input) live inside the menu

A menu button (Bold, Italic) is just a click target — it never needs actual DOM focus,
so the `e.preventDefault()` trick (next section) works fine for it. An `<input>` living
inside the menu is different: it needs **genuine DOM focus** to be typeable at all, and
while the user is typing into it, `editor.isFocused` is legitimately `false` (focus
really did move off the ProseMirror content) — but that must not be treated as "user
clicked away and the menu should hide."

Two things track and protect this state:

```js
const inputFocusedForIndex = {}; // index -> true while a menu input has real DOM focus
```

**1. `mousedown` (capture phase) — deciding whether to `preventDefault()`:**

```js
const isRealFormControl = e.target.closest(
  'input, textarea, select, [contenteditable], [data-allow-focus]'
);
if (!isRealFormControl) {
  e.preventDefault(); // keep editor focused, don't let it blur
}
```

`.closest()` (not `.matches()`) is important here — Bubble typically renders its Input
element wrapped in one or more container `<div>`s, so the actual click target
(`e.target`) is very often that wrapper `div`, not the `<input>` itself. `.matches()`
only checks the exact clicked element and would miss this, incorrectly treating the
input as a plain button and blocking its focus. `.closest()` walks up the ancestor
chain and correctly finds the real form control even when the click lands on a
wrapping element.

**2. `focusin` / `focusout` (capture phase, on `document`) — tracking the lock:**

```js
document.addEventListener('focusin', (e) => {
  // if e.target (or an ancestor) inside this row's menu is a real form control,
  // inputFocusedForIndex[index] = true
}, true);

document.addEventListener('focusout', (e) => {
  // if focus is leaving a menu input AND relatedTarget isn't still inside
  // the same menu (e.g. Tab from the URL field to a "Go" button),
  // inputFocusedForIndex[index] = false, then re-run updateMenuForIndex(index)
}, true);
```

`focusin`/`focusout` (rather than the input's own `focus`/`blur`) are used because they
bubble, so a single `document`-level listener catches focus entering/leaving any menu
input across every row without needing per-input listeners wired up individually.
`focusout`'s `e.relatedTarget` (where focus is headed) is checked so that tabbing
between two controls *within the same menu* doesn't release the lock mid-interaction —
only once focus actually leaves the whole menu is `updateMenuForIndex()` re-run to
decide whether to hide (editor also not focused) or reposition (editor still focused).

Both `updateMenuForIndex()` and the editor's `blur` handler check
`inputFocusedForIndex[index]` first and bail out immediately if true, leaving the menu
exactly as-is while the user is typing.

**Known side effect:** while a menu input holds focus, `editor.isFocused` is `false` —
so a format button clicked in that exact moment won't have a "currently focused editor"
to apply to (Bubble's workflow targets whichever editor was last focused). Clicking
back into the editor content restores focus normally.

