## Keeping the selection highlight visible while a menu input is focused ("fake selection")

**Problem:** the instant real DOM focus moves onto a menu input (e.g. an "Insert Link"
URL field), the browser stops painting its native blue selection highlight over the
text — even though `editor.state.selection` still has the correct `from`/`to` the
whole time (ProseMirror doesn't clear its internal selection on blur; that's exactly
what lets `isFocused`-gated logic elsewhere in this script work). Result: the user
loses the visual cue for which text they're about to apply the link/format to while
they're typing into the menu's own input.

**Fix:** manually paint a substitute highlight over that same `from`/`to` range for as
long as the menu input holds focus, using the browser's own selection-rectangle math
rather than a ProseMirror decoration/plugin (no bundler is available in this vanilla
script environment, so importing `Plugin`/`PluginKey` isn't an option — this approach
only needs read access to the already-rendered DOM):

```js
const fakeSelectionOverlaysForIndex = {}; // index -> array of overlay <div>s currently drawn
const FAKE_SELECTION_COLOR = 'rgba(53, 140, 255, 0.35)'; // <-- CHANGE to match your theme
const FAKE_SELECTION_Z_INDEX = 9998; // just under the menu itself (9999)

function showFakeSelectionForIndex(index) { ... }
function hideFakeSelectionForIndex(index) { ... }
function repositionFakeSelectionForIndex(index) { ... }
```

- `showFakeSelectionForIndex(index)` reads `editor.state.selection`'s `from`/`to`,
  converts each into a real DOM position via `view.domAtPos()`, builds a native
  `Range` from those two points, and calls `range.getClientRects()` — the same
  rectangle math the browser itself uses internally to paint a real selection
  highlight. One `<div>` (fixed-positioned, `pointer-events: none`, `z-index: 9998`)
  is drawn per returned rect, which means wrapped multi-line selections automatically
  get one overlay per visual line rather than a single box that ignores line-wrapping.
- Both `domAtPos()` calls and the `Range` construction are wrapped in `try/catch`: if
  the row's content changes underneath the captured `from`/`to` (e.g. a Bubble
  re-render mid-edit) those positions can go stale, and this fails silently — the
  overlay just doesn't draw rather than throwing. It won't self-heal until focus moves
  again, but this is scoped to "user is filling in a link URL for a couple seconds,"
  so it's an edge case rather than a real risk.
- `hideFakeSelectionForIndex(index)` removes any overlay `<div>`s currently tracked
  for that index and clears the entry.
- `repositionFakeSelectionForIndex(index)` is a full redraw (cheap, since rects are
  cheap to compute) — called from the same `scroll`/`resize` listeners that already
  reposition the menu itself, so the highlight tracks the text underneath it instead
  of drifting once the page moves.

**Wired into the existing focus-tracking, at the exact points where the selection is
still guaranteed correct:**

- `focusin` (capture phase, same listener that sets `inputFocusedForIndex[index] = true`):
  calls `showFakeSelectionForIndex(index)` immediately. This is the reliable moment to
  snapshot the selection — right when real focus lands on the menu's input, before
  ProseMirror or Bubble can do anything else that might invalidate it.
- `focusout` (capture phase, same listener that sets `inputFocusedForIndex[index] = false`):
  calls `hideFakeSelectionForIndex(index)` once focus has genuinely left the whole
  menu (not just moved to another control inside the same menu). If focus returned to
  the editor, the browser's own native highlight resumes automatically at that point;
  if focus left the row entirely, `updateMenuForIndex()` (called right after) also
  hides the menu.
- Outside-click handler: also calls `hideFakeSelectionForIndex(index)` defensively, so
  a click away from the row can't strand a highlight with no menu input focused to
  justify it.

No dedicated ID Attribute is needed on menu inputs for this to work — it reuses the
same generic `input, textarea, select, [contenteditable], [data-allow-focus]` selector
already used for focus tracking, so any current or future menu input (an "Insert Link"
field, for example) is covered automatically.

