## Why menu-button clicks call `e.preventDefault()` on mousedown

```js
```js
const isRealFormControl = e.target.closest(
  'input, textarea, select, [contenteditable], [data-allow-focus]'
);

if (menuEl && menuEl.contains(e.target)) {
  mousedownWasInsideMenu = true;
  if (!isRealFormControl) {
    e.preventDefault(); // keep editor focused, don't let it blur
  }
}
```

Clicking any menu button (Bold, Italic, etc.) is a click *outside* the
`contenteditable` editor itself, so the browser's default behavior is to shift focus
away from the editor and onto (or just off of) that button — which fires the editor's
`blur` event. Calling `e.preventDefault()` on the `mousedown` for menu clicks stops the
browser from ever shifting focus in the first place, so `blur` never fires for a
button click at all: `editor.isFocused` stays `true` the whole time, and the format
button's Bubble workflow (which applies formatting to "the currently focused editor")
keeps working correctly. `preventDefault()` on `mousedown` does **not** block the
subsequent `click`/`mouseup`, so the button's own workflow still fires normally — it
only blocks the focus-shift default action.

Real form controls (`input`, `textarea`, `select`, `[contenteditable]`, or anything
manually flagged with `data-allow-focus`) are excluded from this `preventDefault()` —
see the section above for why, and for the accompanying `focusin`/`focusout` tracking
that keeps the menu from hiding while one of them is focused.

