## Known issues fixed during development (changelog)

1. **Menu only worked on first row** — root cause: plugin's native Bubble Menu
   mechanism relies on `getElementById()`, which only finds the first DOM match when
   IDs repeat across Repeating Group rows. Fixed by building a fully custom
   selection-based menu keyed off row index.
2. **Menu positioned off-screen / ran to screen edges** — fixed with horizontal
   clamping against viewport or an optional bounds element, plus a vertical flip when
   there isn't room above the selection.
3. **First click didn't apply, menu hid on click** — root cause was twofold:
   - An earlier version of this script tried to *also* run the formatting command
     itself (`editor.chain().focus().toggleBold().run()`), which double-applied on
     top of the existing Bubble workflow already doing this — net effect looked like
     "nothing happened" (toggle → toggle back).
   - The show/hide logic checked `view.hasFocus()`, which becomes `false` the instant
     you click any button outside the editor (including the menu itself), causing the
     menu to hide before the user could interact further.
   Fixed by removing all custom command-execution from this script (formatting is
   left entirely to the existing Bubble workflows) and switching the hide condition
   to purely `selection.empty`, with a separate outside-click listener for the
   "clicked elsewhere on the page" case.
4. **Bubble has no native custom `data-*` attribute field** — an earlier attempt used
   a `data-command` attribute for buttons, which Bubble's UI has no field for, so it
   never actually rendered. This became moot once command-execution was removed from
   the script (step 3 above), since formatting is handled by Bubble workflows, not by
   this script reading button attributes.
5. **Menu popped up with no text selected, specifically when arrowing between a
   horizontal rule and a table** — root cause: the show/hide check only looked at
   `selection.empty`. ProseMirror selections aren't all plain text selections:
   arrow-keying past an "atom" node (a horizontal rule, a table) can't place a text
   cursor *inside* that node, so ProseMirror falls back to selecting the whole node
   (`NodeSelection`) or a table cell range (`CellSelection`) instead. Those selection
   types have a non-collapsed `anchor`/`head` even though the user never highlighted
   any text, so `selection.empty` was `false` and the menu showed itself. Fixed by
   also checking the selection's own `type` (via `selection.toJSON().type`, present
   on every ProseMirror selection type) and only showing the menu when
   `type === 'text' && !selection.empty` — i.e. a real, non-collapsed text selection,
   excluding `NodeSelection`, `CellSelection`, and `GapCursor`.

   **Note:** if you ever want the bubble menu to also appear for a click-and-drag
   table cell selection (`CellSelection`), this fix will currently hide it in that
   case too — it was excluded on purpose since the reported bug only concerned
   keyboard navigation, not intentional cell selection.

6. **Menu for a row stopped working after that row was re-rendered by Bubble** —
   root cause: listener attachment was tracked purely by row index
   (`listenersAttachedForIndex.has(index)`). If Bubble destroyed and re-rendered a
   row at the same index (re-sort, filter refresh, live data update), a brand-new
   Tiptap `Editor` instance appeared at that index, but the script saw "already
   attached for this index" and skipped re-attaching `selectionUpdate`/`transaction`
   listeners to the new instance — the row's menu silently stopped updating until a
   full page reload. Fixed by tracking attachment by **editor identity**
   (`attachedEditorByIndex[index] !== editor`) instead of by index alone, so a
   genuinely new instance at the same index gets its listeners re-attached.

7. **Menu stayed visible after clicking outside the editor, until clicking outside a
   second time** — root cause: ProseMirror does not clear its internal selection
   when the editor's DOM focus is lost. An earlier fix attempt hid the menu on
   outside-click and set a "force-hidden" flag meant to survive scroll/resize ticks,
   but that flag was cleared by *any* subsequent `transaction` event — not
   necessarily one caused by real interaction with that row (e.g. a Bubble
   workflow, or an unrelated re-render could fire one). Since the stale selection
   still looked like a valid non-empty text selection, the menu would reappear.
   Fixed properly by gating visibility on `editor.isFocused` directly on every
   call (the authoritative signal, not a flag), and adding a real `editor.on('blur',
   ...)` handler that hides the menu the instant focus genuinely leaves that row.
   The earlier concern that motivated *removing* the focus check in the first place
   — clicking a menu button blurs the editor before its own workflow runs — is now
   solved differently: `e.preventDefault()` on `mousedown` for clicks inside the menu
   stops that blur from happening at all, so button clicks no longer need a focus
   check workaround.

8. **An `<input>` inside the menu (e.g. an "Insert Link" URL field) couldn't be
   focused/typed into at all** — root cause was twofold:
   - The blanket `e.preventDefault()` on every menu `mousedown` (fix #7 above) blocks
     the browser's default *focus* action too, not just the blur it was meant to
     stop. For a plain button that's harmless (buttons don't need real focus), but
     for an `<input>` it meant the input's own "focus me" default action never ran —
     the input was permanently unfocusable even though the menu itself worked fine.
   - The first attempted fix checked `e.target.matches('input, textarea, ...')` to
     decide when to skip `preventDefault()`. This missed cases where Bubble renders
     the actual `<input>` wrapped inside one or more container `<div>`s and the
     `mousedown` lands on that wrapper rather than the input itself — `.matches()`
     only checks the exact clicked element, so the wrapper click was still treated
     as a plain button and still got `preventDefault()`'d.
   Fixed by (a) switching the check to `e.target.closest(...)`, which walks up the
   ancestor chain and correctly finds the real form control even when the click
   lands on a wrapping element, and (b) adding `inputFocusedForIndex` tracking via
   `focusin`/`focusout` listeners so that once the input does have real focus, both
   `updateMenuForIndex()` and the editor's `blur` handler know to leave the menu
   alone instead of hiding it (since `editor.isFocused` is legitimately `false` at
   that point, which would otherwise read as "user clicked away").

9. **Selection highlight disappeared while typing into a menu input (e.g. the
   "Insert Link" URL field)** — root cause: the browser's native selection highlight
   is a rendering effect tied to real DOM focus, not to ProseMirror's internal
   selection state. The moment focus legitimately moved off the editor and onto the
   menu's own input (fix #8, above), the browser stopped painting the blue highlight
   over the selected text, even though `editor.state.selection` still had the
   correct `from`/`to` the entire time — leaving the user with no visual indicator
   of which text they were about to link/format. Fixed by manually drawing a
   substitute highlight: capturing `from`/`to` at the moment the menu input gains
   focus (via the same `focusin` listener that sets `inputFocusedForIndex`),
   converting those positions to real DOM coordinates with `view.domAtPos()` and the
   browser's own `Range.getClientRects()`, and rendering one absolutely-positioned,
   `pointer-events: none` overlay `<div>` per returned rect (so wrapped multi-line
   selections get one overlay per line automatically). The overlay is removed the
   moment focus genuinely leaves the menu (`focusout`) or the row is clicked away
   from entirely, and repositioned on `scroll`/`resize` alongside the menu itself.
   A ProseMirror plugin/decoration approach was considered first but ruled out since
   this vanilla script environment has no bundler to import `Plugin`/`PluginKey` —
   the DOM `Range` approach needed only read access to the already-rendered editor,
   with no internal ProseMirror APIs. See "Keeping the selection highlight visible
   while a menu input is focused" above for the full implementation.
